demographics <- import(here("data", "Teen-Demographic-SPSS(1) copy.zip"))

phys_act <- import(here("data", "Teen-PA-SPSS(1) copy.zip"))

Data Cleaning

Joined Data

Our data was split into two files for size/downloadable reasons: adolescent demographic and adolescent physical activity surveys. Each of these files contained a column containing the variable PID, or participant identification. The PIDs are unique to each individual who completed the surveys. We used this variable to join these two data sets. This was done using the full join function from the dplyr package. This was used so we could retain all variables contained within both data sets for each specific participant identified by their unique PID. After fully joining these two data sets, we then needed to tidy up data using functions from the tidyverse and dplyr packages ## Cleaning data - {select}, {characterize}, and {filter} We then wanted to characterize only select variables, hence the use of the {select}> {characterize} functions. We could not find a way to characterize the data set as a whole without turning some variables values to NA, so we selected certain variables, characterized them, then rejoined the data sets with the newly characterized data.

joined_set <- demographics %>% full_join(phys_act, by = "PID")

join1 <- joined_set %>% 
  as_tibble() %>%
  select(PID, TSEX, TSCHLTYPE, TETHRAC_RC, TGRADE, TAGE) %>% 
  characterize(c(TSEX, TSCHLTYPE, TETHRAC_RC, TGRADE, TAGE))

join2 <- joined_set %>% 
  select(PID,XTHEIGHTCM_RC, XTWEIGHTKG_RC, TETHRAC_RC, TPMPABAD, TPMPAWANT, TPMPAUPST, TPMPAIMPT, XTPREDWEEKS, XTPREDWEEKOFS, XTPREDWEEKW, TAGE)

full_joined_set <- join2 %>% full_join(join1, by = "PID")

Convert -9 to NA and ridding any rows with NAs

final_joined <- full_joined_set %>% 
  replace_with_na_all(condition = ~.x == -9) %>% 
  na.omit(full_joined_set)

Ages 13-18 (teenagers) only {filter}

We chose to focus on adolescence and filtered our new joined and characterized data set to include only participants ages greater than 13. The data used single numbers to equate to age. 1= 11, 2= 12, 3= 13 etc, so we filtered for age >= 3 (equating to 13)

teenage_only <- final_joined %>% 
  filter(TAGE.x >= 3)

Teenagers With BMI Calculated {mutate}

To calculate BMI, we utilized the {mutate} function teen_w_bmi_1 is our cleaned data set. We completed {pivot_wider} and {pivot_longer} but did not include in the cleaned data set because it made it messy.

teen_w_bmi <- teenage_only %>% 
  mutate(height_meters = XTHEIGHTCM_RC / 100) %>% 
  mutate(bmi = XTWEIGHTKG_RC/(height_meters^2)) %>%
  mutate(total_pa_wk_min = XTPREDWEEKOFS + XTPREDWEEKW)

teen_w_bmi_1 <- subset(teen_w_bmi, TSEX!="Not ascertained")
teen_w_bmi_1 <- subset(teen_w_bmi_1, TSCHLTYPE!="Not ascertained")
teen_w_bmi_1 <- subset(teen_w_bmi_1, TGRADE!="Not ascertained")

Calculating Mean Physical Activity and Mean Age according to school type and sex- {summarize} and {group_by}

The {group_by} function allowed us to organize our data by school type and sex to calculate mean physical activity and mean age. This grouping was helpful for our description of the relevant data for our research questions. We ultimately did not ask a research question regarding when physical activity was completed - in school, out of school, or on weekend, but kept in the code because it is interesting).

grouped_data <- teen_w_bmi_1 %>%
  group_by(TSCHLTYPE, TSEX) %>%
  summarize(mean_age = round(mean(TAGE.x + 10), digits = 2),
            mean_total_PA = round(mean(total_pa_wk_min), digits = 2)) %>% 
  kable()

teen_w_bmi_1$TSCHLTYPE <- as.factor(teen_w_bmi_1$TSCHLTYPE) #school type
levels(teen_w_bmi$TSCHLTYPE)
## NULL
rev_teen_w_bmi_1 <- teen_w_bmi_1%>%
   group_by(TSCHLTYPE, TSEX) %>%
  mutate(mean_age = round(mean(TAGE.x + 10), digits = 2),
            mean_total_PA = round(mean(total_pa_wk_min), digits = 2), 
         PA_pct_in_school = (mean(XTPREDWEEKS)/mean_total_PA) *100, 
         PA_pct_out_school = (mean(XTPREDWEEKOFS)/mean_total_PA) *100,
         PA_pct_wkend = (mean(XTPREDWEEKW)/mean_total_PA)*100)

{pivot_longer} for organzing when physical activity occurs

The initial data set divided when physical activity was completed by during the week in school (XTPREDWEEKS), during the week out of school (XTPREDWEEKOFS), and on the weekend(XTPREDWEEKW). Using {pivot_longer}, we combined the variables of when/where the physical activity was completed to explore when/where physical activity was completed across different school types and demographic variables. We used various ggplot functions to visualize the data and associations. 

longer_teen_bmi_1 <- teen_w_bmi_1 %>% 
  pivot_longer(
    cols = starts_with("XTPREDWEEK"), 
    names_to = "MVPA_when", 
    values_to = "minutes", 
    values_drop_na = TRUE) %>% 
  select(PID, TSEX, TGRADE, TSCHLTYPE, MVPA_when, minutes) 

#Column Plot to show break down of when physical activity is completed by grade and sex
longer_teen_bmi_1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(TGRADE, minutes))+
  geom_col(aes(fill=TSEX), 
           position= "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~MVPA_when) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title= "Pattern of Physical Activity by Grade and Sex",
       x= "Grade in School",
       y= "Total Number of Minutes Spend Exercising",
       fill= "Sex") 

#Column plot to show when physical activity is completed by type of school and sex
longer_teen_bmi_1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(TSCHLTYPE, minutes))+
  geom_col(aes(fill=TSEX), 
           position= "dodge") +
  facet_wrap(~MVPA_when) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title= "Pattern of Physical Activity by School Type and Sex",
       x= "Type of School",
       y= "Total Number of Minutes Spent Exercising",
       fill= "Sex")

#Box plot to show when physical activity was completed by school type
longer_teen_bmi_1 %>%
  ggplot(aes(MVPA_when, minutes)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  facet_wrap(~TSCHLTYPE) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle=90, hjust = 1)) +
  labs(title= "Pattern of Physical Activity by Type of School",
       x= "When Physical Activity was Completed",
       y= "Total Number of Minutes Spend Exercising")

#this one is pretty cool to show differences by sex and school type - answer- no difference! 
ggplot(longer_teen_bmi_1, aes(minutes, MVPA_when)) +
  geom_density_ridges(aes(fill = factor(TSEX)), 
                        alpha= 0.5) +
  labs(title = "Physical Activity according ot Sex", 
       x= "Weekly Minutes of Physical Activity", 
       y= "When- During week in school, out of school, or on weekend",
       fill= "Sex")

##{pivot_wider} for School Type Because of the relatively clean data set and types of variables we have, it was challenging to find a useful way to incorporate {pivot_wider} for our research questions. So, we experimented with {pivot_wider} with the TSCHLTYPE variable and broke it down into each school type with participants total minutes of physical activity by week and the average physical activity. It succeeded in pivoting wider and organizing the mean and total weekly physical activity by school type. However, because each participant only attended one school, there are NA values for the schools they did not attend, making the resulting data frame appear messier. After much trial and error, we resolved that we cannot remove the NAs at this time, because they are necessary for the formatting of the data set.

wider_teen_bmi_1 <- teen_w_bmi_1 %>% 
  select(PID, TSCHLTYPE, total_pa_wk_min) %>%
  group_by(TSCHLTYPE) %>%
  mutate(mean_totalpa = mean(total_pa_wk_min)) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = TSCHLTYPE, 
    values_from = total_pa_wk_min)
